In article <strnlghtCDsLqq.AIJ@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
>In article <Junger.157.748718752@samsara.law.cwru.edu>,
>Peter D. Junger <Junger@samsara.law.cwru.edu> wrote:
>
>>The government cannot force a suspect to reveal his encryption key without 
>>forcing him to do something that may--and that the government hopes will--
>>incriminate him.  And the fifth amendment to the federal constitution denies 
>>the government the power to force someone to incriminate himself.  That's 
>>why defendants were not forced to decrypt the materials (and, unless the 
>>fifth amendment is repealed--or ignored by the courts--the government is not 
>>going to be able to force suspects to decrypt their files in the future).
>>
>
>Help me to understand this argument. It seems to fly in the face of the
>government's ability to compel documents during discovery.
>
While not claiming to be any sort of expert on US law, I would guess that
if it is written down or otherwise recorded then the law can allow access,
but if it is in the defendant's head then it can't. So, encrypt everything and
destroy all records of the key :-) 

